In the Midwest, a consortium of states is working together on purchasing supplies to avoid competition that drives up prices.
A depleted Strategic National Stockpile has states competing among themselves and with the federal government for personal protective equipment.
In the Midwest, a consortium of states is working together on purchasing supplies to avoid competition that drives up prices.
Gavin Newsom of California is also using his state’s purchasing power to acquire millions of pieces of protective equipment for his own state’s use and potentially for neighboring states.
But faced with the reality of needing to be proactive on supplies, states are rising to the occasion and helping each other.